					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">infiniteneslives wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I understand exactly what you're saying.<br /><br />The thing that really made these connectors work was the fact there was only .019" of free play.  So you're unable to slid the cart fully to the left and create the scenario seen in the picture you show.<br /><br />To prove it to myself I place a board with all 72 contacts removed from the case in my connector.  Then I tested for continuity and shorting between pins on both sides and the center while the board was slid from side to side.  By testing in this manner I can rule out the argument that my cart isn't using all the pins.  Now I didn't test every single pin in every single position because that I'd still be testing.  But I did test the extremes that have the best chance of causing issues.  If I didn't already have everything assembled I would be willing to do more tests to further prove things if someone desired.  If I buy more connectors in the future I will most likely do such just to prove even more so for myself.<br /><br />The only real way I see problems arising is if certain carts have different lengths of the board edge.  If the board was small enough you may be able short pins together or lose contact.  One could go through and measure various carts with a caliper if they were that concerned.<br /><br />As an aside I'm not necessarily trying to prove you "wrong" I agree there is potential for issues with these connectors.  And if you don't want to use them I'm not going to lose any sleep.  It's not like I'm trying to sell them to anyone.  After buying them I everyone informed me they wouldn't work and gave evidence on paper that they wouldn't.  At the time I regretted buying them and expected to return them.   But with some simple testing with the actual hardware I couldn't find any actual problems.  Personally I'm thrilled with them and very thankful that I actually tested things out and found a solution for at least myself, if no one wants to agree with my results that's fine.  They can continue to search for a solution.</div>
<br />Only having 0.19" (0.48mm) of play is good.  The "sweet spot" where the contention is in the middle of the board is 4 pins wide, or 4 * 2.5mm = 10mm.  So you have a 10mm range in which the contention is occurring on the unused expansion pins, so it shouldn't be too hard to place the cart in this range - and it sounds like mechanically your connector prevents it from going outside this range.  That's good news.
<br />You still seem to be claiming that your connector doesn't have any contentions.  That I do not believe, the math proves it to be impossible, regardless of what your multimeter says <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />.  I certainly trust the math more than your experimentation.  I don't say this to be rude, it's just that math doesn't lie and therefore I cannot trust your experiment.
<br />However, I readily admit that it is possible that my math is flawed.  My diagram shows two pcb edges, it does NOT show the connector itself.  The metal on the connector is probably a little narrower than the trace on the PCB, which might impact the calculation.  Of course the pitch cannot be different, so contention is still unavoidable - but it might not be exactly every 22 pins.  It is also possible that the space between the traces on the pcb edge are not exactly 0.882mm as I have on my diagram.  Again, this could throw off the "22 pin" number - but ultimately does not avoid the problem.
<br />Having admitted the math could be  flawed, I invite someone to show where it is wrong!  You're counter argument is "the connector works", which even if it is true - does not shine any light onto how that could be possible.
<br />I'm glad that your adapter is working for you, it's not my intention to argue about it.  I'm simply trying to get at the truth and to document the reason behind the limitations of using the 2.54mm adapters.
<br />I have an order to place at digikey soon anyway, maybe I'll throw one of these in so I can verify myself.  Or I could dig out the one I bought 8 years ago from digikey, maybe it shrank a bit while resting in the closet <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /></div>

