			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">teaguecl wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">You could line them up at the middle instead, since there are less than 22 pins in each half, right?<br /><br /><img src="http://i51.tinypic.com/15gwidy.png" alt="Image" /></div><br /><br />No, that will not work.  If you lined up the middle perfectly, meaning pin 18, then 11 away from it in either direction you will have a shift of 11 * 0.04 = 0.44mm.  That is a total shift from pin 7 to 29 of 0.88, which is too much.   Remember, the error is in the same direction on both sides.  Ben Heck got around this by splitting the connector in half, thereby sending half the error to the left and half to the right, which does work.  That is also the way your picture above is drawn (error to left of arrows accumulating to left, error on the right accumulating to the right).</div>
<br />
<br />While I frown on the idea of using a 2.54mm pitch connector to interface with an NES cartridge,  it is most likely working because the contact fingers on the connector are quite a bit smaller footprint than the edge connector pins on the cartridges.  The error accumulates, but the footprint on the fingers is small enough that it still works.
<br />
<br />I still think it'll be fiddly and non-optimal, but it will *probably* work.  Most of the time.   This is why I personally don't like the idea of using the 2.54mm pitch connectors.  It will indeed work but there will be cases where it most likely is not going to work.  This could be bad news on a cartridge dumper that has a new mapper you're trying to reverse engineer.  Is it the cart?  The mapper? The connector?</div>

					
